There are three justifications for my forecast. First, the trajectory of Brent crude oil prices indicate that in the remaining trading days between now and 1 October 2018, the spot price will only increase from its current value of $81.85 (https://www.bloomberg.com/energy). Second, the future value of a Brent crude oil contract for November 2018 is priced at $81.81, indicating that prices will remain in excess of $80, with slight fluctuations. (https://www.marketwatch.com/investing/future/brent%20crude?countrycode=uk) Third, recent developments indicate that the closing spot price for Brent crude oil on 1 October 2018 will be significantly above $80 per barrel. Over the weekend, OPEC leaders refused to increase production of Brent crude oil. (https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/24/brent-crude-breaks-80-its-highest-since-2014-as-oil-market-tightens.html) Coupled with sanctions enacted by the United States against Iran, the global supply of oil is predicted to contract, thus increasing the price of oil. (https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/24/brent-crude-breaks-80-its-highest-since-2014-as-oil-market-tightens.html) Recent predictions from multinational investment banks, such as JP Morgan, have speculated that the price of Brent crude oil will exceed $90 a barrel in the upcoming months. Therefore, I contend that the spot price of Brent crude oil at closing time on 1 October 2018 will be in excess of $80 a barrel.

Which country can make up that shortfall of more than 1 million barrels a day for the global market? It’s not entirely clear, according to the IEA. Infrastructure constraints are starting to limit the United States’ ability to keep growing. Brazil’s promised output increases have yet to materialize. Russia says it can pump as much as 300,000 more barrels a day, but likely not until next year. Many OPEC members, such as Iraq, Nigeria, and Libya, have already nearly maxed out their production. That likely leaves Saudi Arabia and a handful of other traditional suppliers. https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/09/13/oil-production-record-levels-why-are-oil-prices-heading-higher-opec-iea-venezuela-iran/

The front-month futures price (what most traders use to gauge what the market is doing) has risen further away from $70 lately [1] corroborating the notion of technical support around that level. Going forward, it will be important to watch whether the market manages to break through the downward trend line formed by connecting the high on 10 July and 8 August. Another possibility is that the market will break below the 200 day moving average (which is around the 70 level), which traders would interpret as a sign portending further losses.

According to analysts the oil price has risen due to uncertainty regarding the US and the Iran nuclear deal. The wider geopolitical is what happens if the US repudiates the deal and the other signatories do not? The US has been able to pressurize the world to into putting trade bans and sanctions on countries by threatening to discriminate against countries that don't join with the US. Generally speaking this has been effective when the US is viewed as upholding international law, but has been less effective when the US has been viewed as acting arbitrarily (e.g. against Cuba). If the US moves toward more unilateral solutions to problems will the other big economies start moving further away from coordinating their international policies with the US? Will other countries move to protect their economies from possible future arbitrary US policies by setting up international systems that can bypass the US? Will the post-WW2 international organisations such as the World Bank, IMF, WTO (formerly GATT), UN etc. become clubs of the international countries with the US just left as an isolationist state? For the last 70 years its economy has been big enough relative to everyone else to dominate, but the relative economic power of the US is declining (as it must as other countries improve their economies). The US still dominates in military power, but China sees the need to balance the US. Will the EU seeing a more isolationist US (or if not isolationist, then a unilateralist US) and a growing China, a Russia, India and others, start to see the need to build it defense capabilities to match its economy? The US says it wants Europe to build up its defenses, but it assumes that Europe would continue to be a junior Allies of the US. Would be US be so happy if Europe thought it needed to build up its military power to protect itself from a unilateralist US?
